The paper focuses on reducing training time in convolutional neural networks (CNNs) through a method that involves downsampling input images and reducing forward pass operations via pooling on convolution filters. This is a common problem in computer vision (CV) and machine learning (ML) research, which suggests that cs.CV and cs.LG are the most likely sub-categories. The paper also involves the use of differentiable pooling, which is a technique used in artificial intelligence (AI) and neural networks (NE), suggesting that cs.AI and cs.NE are also likely sub-categories. Finally, the paper involves experiments on residual architectures, which are commonly used in natural language processing (NLP) and computational linguistics (CL), suggesting that cs.CL is a less likely but still possible sub-category.
